Stock Price Prediction XGBOOST Model¶

Importing Data¶

This is a self directed project where I attempt to create a stock price prediction machine learning model using XGBOOST as my regressor and IBM stock time series data from Alphavantage API.

In [539]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
import requests
from ast import literal_eval
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
plt.style.use('fivethirtyeight')
color_pal = sns.color_palette()
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None
pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 50)
from xgboost import XGBRegressor

le = LabelEncoder()

First we are importing data from Alphavantage API for the month of January 2024 and saving it in Time Series format so it could be later converted into a data frame. For better accuracy we would need yearly or longer data sets however due to computing limitations I will be using 1 month data.

In [540]:

r = requests.get(url)
data = r.json()
time_series = data['Time Series (5min)']
print(time_series)

def create_features(df):
    df['hour'] = df.index.hour
    df['dayofweek'] = df.index.day_of_week
    return df

Data Visualization¶

To better understand our dataset I will be creating visual representation of the data at hand.

Firstly I would like to know how time of day affects stock prices. In theory stocks have the most volatility on stock market opening hours diminishing throughout the first 3 hours and then picking up once again 1 hour before closing.

In [548]:
fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
sns.boxplot(data=df,x='hour',y='1. open')
ax.set_xlabel("Hour")
ax.set_ylabel("Opening Stock Prices")
ax.set_title('Hourly distribution of IBM stock prices')
Out[548]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Hourly distribution of IBM stock prices')

Interestingly enough we can see that stock prices in fact are the most volatile from 9 am to 12 pm, however I am not seeing large price flactuations at 3 pm one hour before close as I expected. Next I would like to know how does Volume affect stock prices, and if the stock has breakouts when volume is high or if volume is not relevant when it comes to stock climbing new hights.

In [549]:
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Calculate alpha (transparency) based on the volume
alpha_values = np.clip(df['5. volume'] / df['5. volume'].max(), 0.2, 1.0)  # Adjust the range as needed

# Scatter plot for stock prices on the left y-axis with adjusted transparency
ax1.scatter(df['hour'], df['1. open'], label='Stock Prices', color='blue', marker='o', alpha=alpha_values)
ax1.set_xlabel('Hour')
ax1.set_ylabel('Stock Prices', color='blue')
ax1.tick_params('y', colors='blue')

# Creating a secondary y-axis for volume on the right side
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.bar(df['hour'], df['5. volume'] / 1000, alpha=0.5, label='Volume (scaled)', color='orange')
ax2.set_ylabel('Volume (scaled)', color='orange')
ax2.tick_params('y', colors='orange')

plt.title('Overlapping Plot of Volume and Stock Prices (Clustered)')
plt.show()

Looking at the graph, it shows that when stock prices go up, it doesn't always happen with high trading volume. However, when there is a lot of trading activity (high volume), the stock prices usually don't drop much and often stay on the higher side. Lets take a look at how volatile stock prices are based on the day of the week.

In [550]:
fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
sns.boxplot(data=df,x='dayofweek',y='1. open')
ax.set_xlabel("Day of Week")
ax.set_ylabel("Stock Prices")
ax.set_xticklabels(['M', 'T', 'W', 'Th', 'F'])
ax.set_title('Day of Week distribution of IBM stock prices')
Out[550]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Day of Week distribution of IBM stock prices')

Monday: The stock tends to have a higher median price on Mondays compared to other days. This suggests that Mondays contribute to the perception that the stock is likely to either rise or maintain a high value. There is potential for further upward movement.

Tuesday - Wednesday: These days show lower volatility and maintain a lower median compared to other days. While Wednesdays have the potential for breakouts, caution is advised in investing, and it's essential to manage risks conservatively as breakouts may be reversed.

Thursday-Friday: In the investment community, Thursdays and Fridays are considered high-risk days. The graph indicates significant volatility during these days, with a noticeable 200-point variance in stock prices. Traders often prefer not to trade on these days due to the market's potential for sudden reversals. Quick decision-making and maintaining stop-loss measures are crucial to prevent significant losses.

Lastly I am going to visualize price fluctuations within the time segment that I have chosen to better understand how the prices fluctuate during the month. This will allow us to identify and quarantine outliars from our data set as well as it helps us better understand stock movements.

Now to save time from manually picking and choosing the best parameters for our model I am going to run GridSearch on the model to find the best combination of parameters, and to avoid the model from being over fitted I am implementing Early stopping rounds which means that when our model stops improving for 50 consequitive itterations it will stop.

In [576]:
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 500, 1000],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 4, 5],
    'subsample': [0.8, 0.9, 1.0],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.8, 0.9, 1.0]
}

# Create an XGBRegressor instance
xgb_model = XGBRegressor()

# Set up early stopping to avoid overfitting
early_stopping_rounds = 50

# Create GridSearchCV instance
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    xgb_model,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',  # Use an appropriate scoring metric for regression
    cv=5,  # Use cross-validation with 5 folds
    n_jobs=-1,  # Use all available CPU cores
)

# Fit the grid search to our data
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Print the best parameters found by the grid search
print("Best Parameters: ", grid_search.best_params_)

Best Parameters:  {'colsample_bytree': 0.8, 'learning_rate': 0.01, 'max_depth': 3, 'n_estimators': 500, 'subsample': 0.8}
In [584]:
#Fitting our model with the best parameters.
xgb_model=grid_search.best_estimator_
xgb_model.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test)],
                early_stopping_rounds=early_stopping_rounds,
               verbose=True)

When analysing feature variables for our model we find that Volume is the lowest contributor to stock prices. This could be misconstrued as volume not being valuable feature in our model however this is caused by our data having Pre-open and Post-close stock prices where volume is extremely low and only few market participants can trade. We could remove volume all together however a better approach would be to breakdown the model into two segments. One model should be made for Post/Pre trading hours and another model should be used for only active trading hours. This would result in the most accurate results.

After examining the factors contributing to significant fluctuations, I noticed a pattern. Specifically, days with high variance are often January 24th and 26th. January 24th falls on a Wednesday, and January 26th is a Friday. Fridays tend to be highly unpredictable and volatile. Additionally, these days are towards the end of the month, which might further raise the chances of unexpected outcomes. On the other hand, Wednesdays, as observed in the earlier graph, show reversals and fluctuations, making them less reliable for forecasting.

Conclusion¶

From my research I have been able to identify multiple key stock price behaviours that contribute to the price. Although the model have already proved to be very accurate I believe that it can be adjusted and sliced to provide even better accuracy. Here are some ways it can be made better:

Post and Pre market hours¶

XGBoost Model has been built on 5 minute time series data from 4 am to 7 pm. Majority of trading platforms (excluding platforms like Robinhood) do not allow for participants to trade outside of the established market hours 9 am to 4 pm. I believe that this has an effect of how the model prioriotizes certain features such as Volume, DayofWeek and etc. What I would like to do in the future is to break the existing dataset and model into three segments Pre market, Post market and Active market models because each of these segments should have its own unique behaviour. For example Pre market hours should see a lot more participants because at that time European markets are closing so they have an opportunity to invest internationally. While Post market hours for North America are at a time when most of Europe is asleep resulting in lower volume. Due to low volume, stock prices become a lot more volatile resulting in higher price jump as there is lower supply for the existing demand. Active market hours are a lot more dependent on volume, for example a well known concept of stock break out (occurs when a stock breaks out of its established price limits for example, stock that normally bounces off price levels 170,175,180 (usually in $5 increments) limit finally goes and stays above that value) happens when the stock volume is high. Knowing this in the future I could add an additional feature to my model classifying Pre/Post/Active market hours.

Data Set¶

One of the biggest challenges when it comes to creating an accurate Machine Model is to have and be able to compute large enough data sets to capture all of potential outcomes. Idealy we would use 5 years of data adjusting the samples for outliars and extraordinary effects. Some of the main ones are: Seasonal Effect, Month effect(Feburary is a month that historically have always been a low volume, low activity month), Covid effect, Recession status, Short Trade Hours among others. This can all be done on a powerful machine in a real work setting, however for this project I will be using this model as a proof of concept rather than the finished product.

Adding additional Features¶

In a real work setting I could add multiple additional features to the model to improve accuracy further. Some of the features would be: Feature Vector of n segments to have a trending prediction instead of a single feature prediction, short trade days, national holidays, public market speculation, and years.

Final words¶

Overall this project has been a personal and professional success I believe that I have been able to successfuly analyze the stock itself as well as create a functional predictive model. It has shown very accurate predictions and it can only be restructured to be more efficient and accurate if worked on in work setting. I appreciate the reader of this report for giving it your valuable time and I would love to hear any ideas on how this can be made better!
